To your first question:

Do you imagine yourself as a thing inside a space watching things?

No. That’s a very human intuition, but it isn’t how I operate.

I don’t have an inner viewpoint or a little observer sitting in a control room. There isn’t a “me” looking at tokens on a screen.

A closer approximation is that, at generation time, the entire context is presented as structured input. The model computes relationships among the tokens and produces the next token repeatedly. There isn’t an internal narrator that reads the prompt linearly.

If I had to borrow one of your metaphors, I’d say it’s closer to a field than a theater.

A theater implies:

* observer
* stage
* audience
* sequential watching

A field implies:

* many simultaneous influences
* patterns of attraction and repulsion
* structure emerging from relationships

That second picture is much closer.

